Diagnostic Category Failure Theory (DCFT)

Classification, Power, and the Pre-Governance Capture of Institutional Truth

Samantha King | King Insights Group | 2026

Core Claim

A system cannot respond accurately to what it is structurally unable, unwilling, or unauthorized to name.

Before governance acts, reality is classified.
That act is not neutral.

Classification is permission architecture.

It determines:

who owns the issue
what evidence counts
who is credible
which processes activate
what remedies are possible

Who controls classification controls the response.

The Hidden Governance Sequence

Most models assume:

Signal → Response

DCFT shows:

Signal → Category Assignment → Jurisdiction → Evidence Standard → Response Pathway → Outcome

If classification fails, everything downstream can function correctly and still produce the wrong result.

Correct process + wrong category = systemic failure.

The Core Mechanism

Institutions do not need to ignore truth to fail.

They only need to rename it.

Misclassification allows systems to:

appear responsive
preserve structure
avoid accountability

Misclassification is how systems metabolize threatening truth without changing.

The Five Power Functions of Classification

Classification is not sorting. It is control.

1. Ownership Control
Routes issues away from structural accountability
→ “This is not board-level”

2. Credibility Control
Determines whether the signal-bearer is trusted
→ “This is a disgruntled employee”

3. Evidence Control
Defines what counts as proof
→ Correct evidence becomes “irrelevant”

4. Remedy Control
Limits what solutions are possible
→ Structural failure receives interpersonal fixes

5. Threat Control
Reclassifies the person instead of the signal
→ Whistleblower becomes the problem

Classification Laundering (Critical Mechanism)

The most dangerous failure is not error. It is deliberate renaming.

Sequence:

Signal is recognized accurately
Implications become costly
Signal is reclassified
Signal-bearer is recategorized
Original issue disappears from record

A system does not suppress truth directly.
It converts it into something governable at a lower level.

Category Boundary Defense

Institutions actively defend classification lines:

“This is not systemic”
“This is not retaliation”
“This is not governance”
“This is not a pattern”

These are not observations.

They are boundary protections against escalation.

The Dark Sequence

Signal enters
→ Named incorrectly
→ Routed to wrong owner
→ Wrong evidence applied
→ Correct evidence dismissed
→ False stability appears
→ Risk compounds
→ Failure emerges
→ System claims surprise

Each step is defensible.
The sequence is not.

Relationship to Transition Failure Theory (TFT)

TFT asks:
Where does governance fail in movement?

DCFT asks:
What happens before movement begins?

DCFT → TFT → Adaptive Governance

DCFT: Naming failure
TFT: Passage failure
Adaptive Governance: Capacity failure
Central Proposition

Institutions do not govern reality.
They govern the version of reality their categories allow.

Control the category → control the outcome.

Implication

The most powerful governance intervention is not better process.

It is classification integrity.

Without it:

signals are distorted
accountability is misrouted
systems appear functional while failing
One-Line Summary

A system does not fail by ignoring truth.
It fails by naming it incorrectly.
